[src:fzf/interactive-computing] In computer science, **interactive computing** refers to software which accepts input from the user as it runs.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] Interactive software includes commonly used programs, such as word processors or spreadsheet applications.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] By comparison, non-interactive programs operate without user intervention; examples of these include compilers and batch processing applications that are pre-programmed to run independently.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] Interactive computing focuses on real-time interaction ("dialog") between the computer and the operator, and the technologies that enable them.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] If the response of the computer system is complex enough, it is said that the system is conducting social interaction; some systems try to achieve this through the implementation of social interfaces.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] The nature of interactive computing as well as its impact on users, are studied extensively in the field of computer interaction.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] Ivan Sutherland is considered the father of interactive computing for his work on Sketchpad, the interactive display graphics program he developed in 1963.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] He later worked at the ARPA Information Processing Techniques Office under the direction of J.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] In a 1965 report, Engelbart published his early experiments with pointing devices, including the computer mouse, for composing and editing on interactive display workstations.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] Engelbart's work on interactive computing at SRI migrated directly to Xerox PARC, from there to Apple, and out into the mainstream.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] Thus, the tree of evolution for interactive computing generally traces back to Engelbart's lab at SRI.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] In December 2008, on the 40th anniversary of his 1968 demo, SRI sponsored a public commemorative event in his honor.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] The need for constant user interaction in interactive computing systems makes it different in many ways from batch processing systems.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] Areas of current research include the design of novel programming models and achieving information security and reliability in interactive computing.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] IPython is a software system for scientific interactive computing, supporting data visualization, event-driven programming and a number of related GUI toolkits.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] The Georgia Institute of Technology's School of Interactive Computing formed in 2007, offering masters and doctoral degrees via collaboration with more than 40 faculties.
[src:fzf/interactive-computing] The Tangible Media Group of MIT, led by Professor Hiroshi Ishii, seeks to seamlessly couple the dual world of bits and atoms by presenting a dynamic physical form to computation.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] fzf is an interactive filter program for any kind of list.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] It implements a "fuzzy" matching algorithm, so you can quickly type in patterns with omitted characters and still get the results you want.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] In this mode, the search is case-insensitive by default, but it becomes case-sensitive if the query contains any uppercase letters.
