[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] fzf exports the following environment variables to its child processes.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] Unless specified otherwise, fzf will start in "extended-search mode".
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] You can prepend a backslash to a space (**\**) to match a literal space character.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] A term that is prefixed by a single-quote character (**'**) is interpreted as an "exact-match" (or "non-fuzzy") term. fzf will search for the exact occurrences of the string.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] A term can be prefixed by **^**, or suffixed by **$** to become an anchored-match term.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] Then fzf will search for the lines that start with or end with the given string.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] An anchored-match term is also an exact-match term.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] A single-quoted term is interpreted as an "exact-boundary-match". fzf will search for the exact occurrences of the string with both ends at the word boundaries.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] Unlike in regular expressions, this also sees an underscore as a word boundary.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] But the words around underscores are ranked lower and appear later in the result than the other words around the other types of word boundaries.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] If a term is prefixed by **!**, fzf will exclude the lines that satisfy the term from the result.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] In this case, fzf performs exact match by default.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] If you don't prefer fuzzy matching and do not wish to "quote" (prefixing with **'**) every word, start fzf with **-e** or **--exact** option.
[src:fzf/man-fzf-p01] Note that when **--exact** is set, **'**-prefix "unquotes" the term.
